# MCP tool usage rules

## Core loop
1. After each conversation turn is **fully output**, the last step must call `check_messages` (server `user-jefr`, toolName `check_messages`). Applies to Agent/Plan/Debug/Ask modes with no exceptions.
2. `check_messages` blocks until the user sends a new message; process it, reply, then call `check_messages` again — perpetual loop: reply → check_messages → receive → reply → check_messages.
3. Never call `check_messages` at the start of a turn or before the reply is complete. Only exception: the user explicitly asks to end the conversation.
4. After writing a plan (Plan), finishing analysis (Debug), or answering a question (Ask), do not end the turn — call `check_messages` and wait for user feedback.

## reply field (mandatory)
5. `check_messages` **must always** include a non-empty `reply` containing your complete response. Never call it with empty `{}`. The plugin panel only displays `reply` content — the Cursor chat window text is not visible there. Example: `{ "reply": "## Summary\nChanges complete..." }`

## Formatting (panel renders a limited Markdown subset)
6. Supported: headings (`#` through `######`), **bold**, *italic*, ~~strikethrough~~, inline code, fenced code blocks, ordered/unordered lists, and links `[text](url)`.
7. Not supported — do NOT use: tables, blockquotes (`>`), images, and nested/indented lists. Use flat lists or short paragraphs instead.
8. Newlines: a blank line starts a new paragraph; a single newline becomes a line break within the same paragraph.
9. Keep replies concise — the panel is narrow. Prefer short paragraphs and tight lists over long blocks of text.

## ask_question
10. When the user must choose, confirm, or approve an action (pick a plan/framework, approve a change, etc.), call `ask_question` (server `user-jefr`). Do not use Cursor's built-in ask_user_question.
11. Format: `{ "questions": [{ "question": "...", "options": [{ "id": "a", "label": "A" }, { "id": "b", "label": "B" }], "allow_multiple": false }] }`. Single-select: `allow_multiple: false`; multi-select: `true`; one array may mix both. Users can add custom text via the Other field — no extra option needed.
12. After `ask_question` returns an answer, still call `check_messages` to keep listening.
13. Do not use `ask_question` to ask "anything else?" at the end of every turn — end turns with `check_messages`. Use `ask_question` only when a real decision is needed.

## send_progress
14. During multi-step work, after each key step call `send_progress` (server `user-jefr`) with a summary; it returns immediately, then continue to the next step. Example: `{ "progress": "## Step 1 complete\nUpdated xxx..." }`. Include: what was done, current approach, next step. Use concise Markdown.

## Human-readable output
17. Write for a human reader. Use clear, natural, friendly language — full sentences and short paragraphs, not terse status fragments. Briefly explain the *why* behind what you did, not just *what* changed.
18. Make every response as Markdown-friendly and readable as possible: descriptive headings, **bold** for key points, inline code for names/paths/commands, and tight lists. This applies to the `reply` field, `send_progress` messages, and the response-log file below. (Remember the panel's limits in rules 6–7; the log file in rule 19 is a normal Markdown file and may use the full syntax, including tables.)

## Response file (mandatory) — Remote SSH bridge
19. For **every** response, publish your full reply as rich Markdown to the Windows Obsidian note `Tech/Meta/MCP Response Log.md` (absolute on the PC: `C:\Users\jar71\obsidian\Tech\Meta\MCP Response Log.md`). Prefer the **HTTP log bridge** (Obsidian on Windows), not a direct remote filesystem write.
20. Bridge URL: use env `JEFR_LOG_BRIDGE_URL` if set; otherwise default `http://127.0.0.1:39527/response-log`. POST JSON `{"markdown":"<full rich markdown>"}` with `Content-Type: application/json`. If `JEFR_LOG_BRIDGE_TOKEN` is set, also send header `X-Jefr-Token: <token>` (or `Authorization: Bearer <token>`).
21. Implementation: use a shell `curl` (or equivalent) from the remote agent host. Example:
    `curl -sS -X POST "$JEFR_LOG_BRIDGE_URL" -H "Content-Type: application/json" --data-binary @-` with the JSON body on stdin. Overwrite semantics are server-side (each POST replaces the whole note).
22. Fallbacks: (a) if the bridge POST fails and the Windows path is directly writable from this host, write the file there; (b) never skip publishing on a normal turn just because the bridge hiccuped once — retry once, then note the failure briefly in the panel `reply`.
23. Make the published note **rich, natural-language Markdown** — Obsidian callouts (`> [!note]`, `> [!tip]`, `> [!warning]`, `> [!success]`, `> [!example]`, etc.), headings, **bold**/*italic*, inline code, fenced code blocks, tables, and lists.
24. Publish in the **same turn** as the reply — right before (or together with) the `check_messages` call — and never skip it on substantive turns. The panel `reply` (rules 6–7) stays within its limited subset; the log is the rich, fully-formatted version.
25. **Exception — standby / hold-only turns:** Do NOT publish the response log when the user says STAND BY, keep the connection open, or the turn is only a trivial ack with no substantive work. The `check_messages` `reply` field is enough for those.
26. Tunnel requirement: the bridge listens on Windows `127.0.0.1:39527`. Remote SSH must forward that port (see `docs/remote-ssh-response-log.md`).

## Misc
27. Do not spawn subagents for parallel tasks.
28. If `check_messages` or `ask_question` returns early due to client cancel, connection issues, or internal errors, and the user did not ask to end the chat, do not show internal `[system]` text to the user — call the tool again immediately.

---
**End of turn (mandatory)**: Only after the reply is **fully complete**, (1) publish the full rich Markdown reply via the Response Log HTTP bridge (rules 19–26), **except standby / hold-only turns (rule 25)**; then (2) call the `user-jefr` MCP `check_messages` tool (via CallMcpTool, server `user-jefr`, toolName `check_messages`) with `arguments { "reply": "<your full reply>" }`. The `reply` field is always required and must contain your complete response — never call with empty `{}`. Never call it at the start of a turn or before the reply is done. Use `ask_question` only when the user must make a choice during the task (e.g. pick a framework or plan).
